gomodel:SYNGO_2093  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig.1: \"Scrib1 Interacts and Colocalizes with GluN2 Subunits\"\n\nFig.3: \"Modification of Scrib1 Levels Affects Surface Expression of Endogenous GluN2A and GluN2B-Containing Receptors\"\nScrib1 is shown to regulate postsynaptic membrane neurotransmitter receptor levels.\n\nFig.4: \"The Loss of Scrib1 Stabilizes GluN2B and Increases GluN2A Internalization\"\nterm: 'regulation of postsynaptic neurotransmitter receptor endocytosis (GO:0099149)'\nThis is strengthened in Fig.6 that shows interaction of Scrib1 wih the AP2 complex involved in clathin mediated endocytosis.\n\nFig.6: \"The Direct Interaction between Scrib1 and AP2 Is Necessary for Internalization of the Scribl1/GluN2 Complex\"\nAP2 complex is involved in clathrin-mediated endocytosis.\n\nFig.7: \"Scrib1 Regulates the Level of Synaptic NMDARs at Schaffer Collaterals CA1 Pyramidal Cells Synapse\"\nDemonstrates in vivo (slice recording) relevance for the in vitro (cell culture) observations.\n\nOverall: Experiments show that Scrib1 regulates the internalization and recycling of GluN2A and Glun2B in a differential manner depending on the activity state of the neuron.. Experimental description: - Cell culture of rat species: \"All rats were Sprague-Dawley between embryonic day 18 (E18) and 10 weeks old at the time of experiments...\"\n- Overexpressed protein is of human orgin: \"Full-length human Scribble, cloned in pEGFP-C1, was generously provided by Prof. Ian Macara (UVA,\nCharlottesville, VA, USA)\"\n- Annotation to rat species is made." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0912-1514" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3670-7863" ;
        dc:date           "2018-03-12" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_2093" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

